<doc id="340" url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=340" title="Alain Connes">
Alain Connes

Alain Connes (; born 1 April 1947) is a French </entity/>mathematician mathematician, currently Professor at the </entity/>Collège-de-France Collège-de-France, </entity/>IHÉS IHÉS, </entity/>The-Ohio-State-University The-Ohio-State-University and </entity/>Vanderbilt-University Vanderbilt-University.
Work.
Alain Connes studies </entity/>operator-algebra operator-algebras. In his early work on </entity/>von-Neumann-algebras von-Neumann-algebras in the 1970s, he succeeded in obtaining the almost complete classification of injective </entity/>Von-Neumann-algebra#Factors </mention/>factors. Following this he made contributions in </entity/>K-theory </mention/>operator-K-theory and </entity/>index-theory index-theory, which culminated in the 
</entity/>Baum-Connes-conjecture Baum-Connes-conjecture. He also introduced </entity/>cyclic-homology </mention/>cyclic-cohomology in the early 1980s as a first step in the study of </entity/>noncommutative-geometry </mention/>noncommutative-differential-geometry.
Connes has applied his work in areas of </entity/>mathematics mathematics and </entity/>theoretical-physics theoretical-physics, including </entity/>number-theory number-theory, </entity/>differential-geometry differential-geometry and </entity/>particle-physics particle-physics.
Awards and honours.
Connes was awarded the </entity/>Fields-Medal Fields-Medal in 1982, the </entity/>Crafoord-Prize Crafoord-Prize in 2001 and the gold medal of the </entity/>CNRS CNRS in 2004. He is a member of the </entity/>French-Academy-of-Sciences French-Academy-of-Sciences and several foreign academies and societies, including the </entity/>Royal-Danish-Academy-of-Sciences-and-Letters </mention/>Danish-Academy-of-Sciences, </entity/>Norwegian-Academy-of-Science-and-Letters </mention/>Norwegian-Academy-of-Sciences, </entity/>Russian-Academy-of-Sciences Russian-Academy-of-Sciences, and </entity/>United-States-National-Academy-of-Sciences </mention/>US-National-Academy-of-Sciences.
