<doc id="344" url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=344" title="Allan Dwan">
Allan Dwan

Allan Dwan (3 April 1885 – 28 December 1981) was a pioneering Canadian-born American motion picture director, producer and screenwriter.
Early life.
Born Joseph Aloysius Dwan in </entity/>Toronto,-Ontario Toronto,-Ontario, Canada, Dwan moved with his family to the United States when he was eight (8) years old, on April 15, 1893. At the </entity/>University-of-Notre-Dame University-of-Notre-Dame, he trained as an engineer and began working for a lighting company in Chicago. However, he had a strong interest in the fledgling motion picture industry and when </entity/>Essanay-Studios Essanay-Studios offered him the opportunity to become a scriptwriter, he took the job. At that time, some of the </entity/>East-Coast-of-the-United-States </mention/>East-Coast movie makers began to spend winters in California where the climate allowed them to continue productions requiring warm weather. Soon, a number of movie companies worked there year-round and, in 1911, Dwan began working part-time in Hollywood. While still in New York, in 1917 he was the founding president of the East Coast chapter of the </entity/>Motion-Picture-Directors-Association Motion-Picture-Directors-Association. 
Career.
Dwan operated </entity/>Flying-A-Studios Flying-A-Studios in </entity/>La-Mesa,-California La-Mesa,-California from August 1911 to July 1912. Flying A was one of the first motion pictures studios in California history. On 12 August 2011, a plaque was unveiled on the Wolff building at Third Ave and La Mesa Bl commemorating Dwan and the </entity/>Flying-A-Studios Flying-A-Studios origins in </entity/>La-Mesa,-California La-Mesa,-California. 
After making a series of westerns and comedies, Dwan directed fellow Canadian-American </entity/>Mary-Pickford Mary-Pickford in several very successful movies as well as her husband, </entity/>Douglas-Fairbanks Douglas-Fairbanks, notably in the acclaimed 1922 "</entity/>Robin-Hood-(1922-film) </mention/>Robin-Hood". Following the introduction of the </entity/>sound-film </mention/>talkies, in 1937 he directed child-star </entity/>Shirley-Temple Shirley-Temple in "</entity/>Heidi Heidi" and "</entity/>Rebecca-of-Sunnybrook-Farm-(1938-film) </mention/>Rebecca-of-Sunnybrook-Farm" the following year. 
Dwan helped launch the career of two other very successful Hollywood directors, </entity/>Victor-Fleming Victor-Fleming, who went on to direct "</entity/>The-Wizard-of-Oz-(1939-film) </mention/>The-Wizard-of-Oz" and "</entity/>Gone-with-the-Wind-(film) </mention/>Gone-With-the-Wind", and </entity/>Marshall-Neilan Marshall-Neilan, who became an actor, director, writer and producer. Over a career spanning almost is long career spanning 50 years, Dwan directed over 400 motion pictures, many of them highly acclaimed, such as the 1949 box office smash, "</entity/>Sands-of-Iwo-Jima Sands-of-Iwo-Jima". He directed his last movie in 1961. 
He died in Los Angeles at the age of ninety-six, and is interred in the </entity/>San-Fernando-Mission-Cemetery San-Fernando-Mission-Cemetery, </entity/>Mission-Hills,-California Mission-Hills,-California.
Allan Dwan has a star on the </entity/>Hollywood-Walk-of-Fame Hollywood-Walk-of-Fame at 6263 </entity/>Hollywood-Boulevard Hollywood-Boulevard.
Further reading.
